<h1 id="Julia-Problem-2:-Define-a-Row-Vector">Julia Problem 2: Define a Row Vector<a class="anchor-link" href="#Julia-Problem-2:-Define-a-Row-Vector">&#182;</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>(1 pt) Julia, somewhat like python, and  unlike MATLAB has vectors which are different from 1 x n or n x 1 matrices.
A row vector is created by placing elements between square brackets with commas separating elements, e.g. [1,1,2,4,6,3] <br></p>
<p>Why does Julia do it this way?  Answer: There are many data science applications where
one dimensional structures are extremely important.</p>
<p>Write Julia code that creates the vector y=[3 5 2 1].</p>
<p>Julia indicates that the result is a 4-element array of 64 bit integers that is 1-dimensional, in other words, a vector!</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

</pre></div>

<h1 id="Julia-Problem-3:-Define-a-One-Column-Matrix-(there-are-no-column-vectors!)">Julia Problem 3: Define a One Column Matrix (there are no column vectors!)<a class="anchor-link" href="#Julia-Problem-3:-Define-a-One-Column-Matrix-(there-are-no-column-vectors!)">&#182;</a></h1>

<p>(1 pt) In Julia one creates a one column matrix by placing elements between square brackets, with spaces separating elements, and then using apostrophe as a transpose: e.g. [1  1  2]' <br></p>
<p>What really happens here is that [1 1 2] is a 1x3 two dimensional matrix, and the apostrophe
turns it into a 3x1 two dimensional matrix.</p>
<p>Write Julia code that creates the 5x1 matrix  <table></p>
<p><tr> <th> 1 </th>  </tr></p>
<p><tr> <th> 2 </th> </tr></p>
<p><tr> <th> -1  </th> </tr></p>
<p><tr> <th> 0 </th> </tr></p>
<p><tr> <th> 0 </th></tr>
</table></p>

</div>
